Vice President Kamala Harris visited Northfield High School in Denver, Colorado, and addressed a group of young leaders who are passionate about climate action. She commended their activism and highlighted the importance of young leaders in driving progress. Harris praised the students for their efforts in organizing and advocating for a climate action plan, which led to Denver Public Schools becoming one of the first school districts in the nation to adopt such a plan. She emphasized the urgency of addressing the climate crisis and discussed the Biden administration's commitment to investing in climate initiatives, such as funding electric school buses, removing lead pipes, and promoting clean energy projects. Harris urged the students to continue their activism and organize during the summer break, emphasizing that their voices and actions are crucial in the fight against climate change.